y on' b'i cor. although boswell suggests that the passage is strange, it may be that' b'paul is seeking to make a refinement in arsenokoitai.' b'12. apparently jerome is a significant omission here, since he renders' b'arsenokoitai as "masculorum concubitores," corresponding "almost exactly to the' b'greek" n.36).' b'' b'footnotes:' b'_______________________' b'5. d.s. bailey, homosexuality and the western christian tradition. (london:' b'1975) b'6. j. boswell, christianity, social tolerance and homosexuality (chicago:' b'1980).' b'several tranlation of i tim are: kjv, "them that defile themselves' b'with mankind"; asv, "abusers of themselves with men"; nasb, "homosexuals";' b'rsv, nkjv, nrsv, "sodomites"; neb, niv, "perverts"; gnb, "sexual perverts"; in' b'i cor these occur: kjv, "abusers of themselves with mankind"; asv,' b'"abusers of themselves with men"; nasb, rsv, "homosexuals"; nkjv, "sodomites";' b'neb, "homosexual persversion." the rsv and neb derive their translation from' b'two greek words, malakoi and arsenokoitai which gbn has as "homosexual' b'perverts." nrsv has the two words as "male prostitutes" in the text, and' b'"sodomites" in the footnote. the active idea predominates among the' b'commentators as well; it is the primary assumption.' b'7. boswell, christianity yet this was no a word "available to paul for' b'a male prostitute," for it does not occur at all in any literature prior to' b'paul (as a serach in the thesaurus linguae graecae using ibycuc confirms). if' b'paul coined the term, it would have no prior history, and all such discussion' b'about its lack of usage in contemporary non-christian and christian literature' b'is meaningless.' b'8. again this would be expected if paul coined the word.' b'9. the key phrase here apparently is "discussoin," for boswell admits later' b'(350 n.42) that it occurs in quotes of paul but there is no discussion in the' b'context. hence the implication is that we cannot tell what these writer' b'(polycarp "to